import javax.swing.*;

public class ButtonExample {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    // Create a new button
    JButton button = new JButton("Click me!");

    // Add an action listener to the button
    button.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
      @Override
      public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        System.out.println("Button clicked!");
      }
    });

    // Create a new frame and add the button to it
    JFrame frame = new JFrame("Button Example");
    frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
    frame.getContentPane().add(button, BorderLayout.CENTER);
    frame.pack();
    frame.setVisible(true);
  }
}
[/PYTHON]
This is the full Java code for a button that displays "Button clicked!" in the console when clicked.

Explanation:

1. The first line imports the necessary classes from the javax.swing package to create a new button and frame.
2. The second line creates a new JButton object with the label "Click me!".
3. The third line adds an action listener to the button, which is a function that will be called when the button is clicked. In this case, it simply prints "Button clicked!" to the console.
4. The fourth line creates a new JFrame object and sets its title to "Button Example".
5. The fifth line sets the default close operation of the frame to exit when the user closes it.
6. The sixth line adds the button to the frame's content pane using the BorderLayout manager.
7. The seventh line calls the pack() method on the frame to size it appropriately based on its contents.
8. The eighth line sets the visibility of the frame to true, making it visible to the user.

Note: This code assumes that you have already set up your development environment and can run Java code. If you haven't, you may need to consult a separate tutorial or guide on how to do so.
